1c. Measures of center

Scientists use measures of center to describe the overal properties of a group, but also to make comparisons among groups.

Youll see sentences in results sections of papers like: Flies that were fed a reduced-protein diet had average wing sizes that were smaller (3.2 mm plus or minues 0.2 mm) than flies that were fed a control diet (6.7 mm plus or minues 0.35 mm).

There are three main ways to calculate the center of a distribution of data, the mean, median and mode.

What are they?

Mean = sum everything, divide the number of things you summed. Median = the most middle number (the middlest?), if there are two, average the two in the middle. Mode = the most common (this is used a lot less, and there actually isnt a built-in function in R for it). R has built in functions that do this for us.

Lets practice:

Well have an example later of instances where its best to use median versus mode, but overall the rule is:
1. Use mean if you have a big sample size that is normally distributed. 2. Use median if you have a smaller sample size that is skewed.

General Problems students will come up with:
1. Only showing averages, no idea of the spread of the data - can we draw accurate conclusions just from averages? 2. Other graphical problems 3. Data exists above the average and below the average, but it looks like there is only data below the average (bar charts suck).

Lets make a better chart.

msleep %>%
  filter(!is.na(vore)) %>%
ggplot(aes(x = factor(vore), y = sleep_total, group = factor(vore))) +
  geom_jitter(width = 0.2, size = 3, alpha = 0.6) + 
  theme_classic() +
  geom_linerange(stat = "summary",
                  fun.ymin = function(z) {quantile(z, 0.25)},
                  fun.ymax = function(z) {quantile(z,0.75)}, fun.y = "median") +
  stat_summary(fun.y = "median", size = 4, color = "blue", geom = "point", alpha = 0.6)

This code is pretty complex. Dont worry too much about it the structure (thuogh remember what we built here so you can poach code at some point down the road)!

2. Different ways to talk about variance and error

There are different ways of quantifying error. Lets talk about them, their definitions, their usefulness and how theyre calculated.

2a. Tools to describe variance

Variance is a numerical description of how a set of data sits around the mean of that data. * High variance = lots of spread. * Low variance = not much spread.

What does this look like?

#Let's generate some fake data. 2 populations of rabbits, where we measured ear length. 

library(tidyverse)
set.seed(42)
pop1 = data.frame(ear_length = rnorm(mean = 25, n = 123, sd = 5),
                  population = "pop1")
pop2 = data.frame(ear_length = rnorm(mean = 25, n = 145, sd = 2),
                  population = "pop2")
hop = as.tibble(bind_rows(pop1, pop2))
## Warning in bind_rows_(x, .id): Unequal factor levels: coercing to character
## Warning in bind_rows_(x, .id): binding character and factor vector,
## coercing into character vector

## Warning in bind_rows_(x, .id): binding character and factor vector,
## coercing into character vector
ggplot(hop, aes(x = ear_length, fill = population)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.5) +
  theme_classic()

Questions for the groups (10 minutes and then report out)
1. Which population has the highest variance? How can you tell?
2. Does the population mean have any effect on the populations variance?
3. What sort of (biological) conclusions might you draw about these two populations? What hypotheses would you make for why we see differences in variance in ear length?

Ok, so we can see the variance, but can we quantify it? Yep.

#Variance caluclation for rabbit population 1
var(hop[hop$population == "pop1",]$ear_length)
## [1] 27.12475
#Variance calculation for rabbit population 2
var(hop[hop$population == "pop2",]$ear_length)
## [1] 3.29197

2a. Standard Deviation

Standard deviation is another measure people use frequently - its just the square root of the variance - its nice because the units are the same as the mean.
R has a function for sd as well!

#Showing that that the square root of the variance is the calculation for the SD
#Square root of the variance
var(hop[hop$population == "pop1",]$ear_length)^(0.5)
## [1] 5.208142
#Using the SD function
sd(hop[hop$population == "pop1",]$ear_length)
## [1] 5.208142

2b. Standard Error of the Mean

Youll also see people throw around standard error of the mean. The standard error is simply the standard deviation divided by the square root of the sample size.
This serves a different purpose than standard deviation. SD gives you information about the spread and variability of your data. SEM gives you infromation about the precision of your mean, or looking at differences between groups.

No built in function.

#Writing a short SEM function
sem = function(x) {
  sd(x)/sqrt(length(x))
}

#calculating the SEM for 
sem(hop[hop$population == "pop1",]$ear_length)
## [1] 0.4696024

Lets go back to the Mammal sleep dataset

sleep_summary = msleep %>%

    group_by(vore) %>%
      summarise(N = length(sleep_total),
                mean = mean(sleep_total),
                sd = sd(sleep_total),

2d. 95% confidence intervals

And finally, 95% confidence intervals. The be all, end all for stats in science. :/
Formal definition: frequency of possible confidence intervals that contain the true value of their corresponding parameter. So a 95% confidence interval of the mean means that here, if we sampled the data an infinite number of times, 95% of the confidence intervals that we would generate would contain the mean.

Practical definition: if your confidence intervals overlap a lot, your means arent different from each other. If they dont overlap, your means are probably different. There is a lot of debate about the history and utility of confidence intervals, which you will probably encounter. Just be prepared.

Here is how we calculate them:

#Same plot as before:
msleep %>%
  filter(!is.na(vore)) %>%
ggplot(aes(x = factor(vore), y = sleep_total, group = factor(vore))) +
  geom_jitter(width = 0.2, size = 3, alpha = 0.6) + 
  theme_classic() +
  stat_summary(fun.y = "mean", size = 4, color = "blue", geom = "point", alpha = 0.6) +
  stat_summary(fun.data = mean_cl_normal, geom = "linerange")

2e. IQR (Interquartile Range)

Formally, the distance that contains 50% of your data (between the 1st and 3rd quartile). Most commonly shown in boxplots, which ARE THE FAR SUPERIOR VERSION OF BAR CHARTS. Also, were not really going to talk about distribution skews in here, but IQR is pretty robust to skewed distributions.

#Chart example - basic
library(dplyr)
msleep %>%
ggplot(aes(x = factor(order), y = log(awake))) +
  geom_boxplot(outlier.alpha = 0) +
  geom_jitter(width = 0.2, size = 2, alpha = 0.4) + 
  theme_classic() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))

#Would probably be nice to get rid of orders that don't have a lot of examples in them. 
detach(package:Hmisc)
msleep$order = factor(msleep$order)


to_keep = msleep %>%
  group_by(order) %>%
  dplyr::summarize(n = n()) %>%
  filter(n > 1) %>%
  pull(order)


#Ideal figure
msleep %>%
  filter(order %in% to_keep) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = order, y = awake)) +
  geom_boxplot(outlier.alpha = 0) +
  geom_jitter(width = 0.1, size = 2, alpha = 0.4) +
  theme_classic() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1)) +
  xlab("Order") +
  ylab("log hours awake")
